I am proud to be the least talented Asian to ever perform piano at Carnegie Hall. It was maybe one of the most terrifying experiences of my life and I am so grateful it is over!!!! Thank you @ramieegan for putting together such a beautiful show and including me in such wonderful company.

It was a daunting task, to find someone I could trust with the retelling of such a personal story. Someone who could honor my mother’s character and respect the darkest days of grief, and still make the coming of age of a half Korean artsy outsider in a small Pacific Northwest hippie town seem real and cool.

In that spirit, I am so relieved to have found Will Sharpe and am beyond delighted that he will be the director of Crying in H Mart. I believe his sensitivity, as a director and an actor, and his own personal experience, having also grown up between two cultures, will be tremendous assets.

His work on Flowers and the Electrical Life of Louis Wain speak to his ability to conjure lofty, vulnerable performances, to find humor and grace within the tragedy of the everyday. They are a precious collection of talents that make him the perfect fit for this film.

ICYMI The @barnesandnoble exclusive paperback edition of Crying of in H Mart includes 24 old photographs of my family with captions. 

“Now that she was gone, there was no one left to ask about these things. The knowledge left unrecorded died with her. What remained were documents and my memories, and now it was up to me to make sense of myself, aided by the signs she left behind. How cyclical and bittersweet for a child to retrace the image of their mother. For a subject to turn back to document their archivist.”

Limited signed copies are available at the link in bio.

She also happens to be a writer and is currently adapting her 2021 best selling memoir “Crying in H Mart” into a screenplay… but confesses that if she weren’t a musician (or a famous author), she’d be running a Korean restaurant.

JB and @ichikoaoba tonight at the big ol Radio City!!!

Words can’t express how much I love Ichiko’s music and how grateful I am she has joined us on these last shows. I discovered her music traveling alone in Sweden, she was a perfect companion as I walked through the cold streets of old town and rediscovered a bit of myself through lonely travel. Since then her music has often soothed me to sleep or through stressful flights when nothing else seems to bring me the same peace and wonder. The best part of my job is I now get to call her my friend. Please make sure to come early to catch her set. We are so lucky!
